Scenario 1: “It Worked Yesterday”
A web application worked correctly during system testing. After a small UI change was deployed, users report that submitting a form intermittently fails.
Questions:

Which testing principle explains why this defect was not previously detected?
What type of testing activity could help prevent similar issues in the future?
Does the failure indicate poor initial testing? Explain.

Answers
1. The Pesticide Paradox explains this; existing tests did not expose new defects introduced by change.
2. Regression Testing could be helpful in this scenario as it tests targeted changes and functionality.
3. No it does not indicate poor testing. Even well-tested software can fail
